  "text": "Smokers showed a negative correlation (−0.102 of the partial regression coefficient) with the dose-effect relationship for IRM recession. Smokers exhibited a higher degree of adipose change with the same IRM thickness as compared with nonsmokers; that is to say, the amount of fibrous tissue in the IRM was lower in smokers than in nonsmokers, although the volume of the IRM was similar. This resulted in less stiffness and inextensibility of the IRM in smokers, causing the negative correlation. Oxidative stress after smoking disturbs lipoprotein metabolism [CITATION_1] , which may be associated with adipose tissue accumulation in the IRM.",
